 to derive definitions of “irony” inductively, showing how writers employed it as a keyword both before and in opposition to the institutionalization of New Criticism. It focuses on writers who not only composed ironic texts but talked about irony and satire to situate their work politically: Randolph Bourne, Benjamin De Casseres, Ellen Glasgow, John Dos Passos, Ralph Ellison, and many others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aIrony in literature. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aPolitics and culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics in literature. 0aSatirexHistory and criticism. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aAmerican literature.  aculture.  airony.  amodernism.  anovel.  apolitics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082325545040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082325547440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823255474423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823255474/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EB